Overview
\par \pard\plain \s2\sa43\keep \f2\fs20\cf6 ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\par \pard\plain \s6\li360\sa31 \f2\fs16 Minesweeper is a challenging game of strategy and luck.  You are
 presented with a mine field, and your objective is to locate all the mines as quickly as possible.  To accomplish this task, you have two tools:  one is a mine detector, the other is your foot.
\par 
\par In order to locate the mines using these limited tools, use the following approach:  
\par \pard\plain \s14\fi-360\li720\sa43\tx720 \f2\fs16 1\tab Step on a square with your foot.
\par 2\tab If the square is a mine, you're dead.
\par \pard\plain \s7\fi-360\li720\sa180\tx720 \f2\fs16 3\tab If the square isn't a mine, your mine detector informs you of the number of mines in the surrounding eight squares.  
\par \pard\plain \s6\li360\sa31 \f2\fs16 Continue to step on squares until you either uncover all the squares without mines and win or step on a mine and die.
\par 
\par You can use the counters at the top of the playing area to keep track of your progress.
\par 
\par The counter in the upper-left corner of the playing area initially indicates the number of mines hidden in the mine field.  Every time you {\ul mark}{\v Mark} a square, this number decreases by one.
\par 
\par The counter in the upper-right corner of the playing area is a timer, which displays your playing time in seconds.  The faster you find all the mines, the better your score.
